# ft_irc

A lightweight Internet Relay Chat server written in C++ as part of the 42 Network curriculum.

This project implements a basic IRC server capable of handling multiple clients simultaneously using socket programming and non-blocking I/O. It follows core IRC protocol concepts such as authentication, nicknames, users, channels, private messages, and channel moderation commands.

## Overview

`ft_irc` is designed to reproduce the behavior of a real IRC server at a simplified scale. Clients can connect to the server using an IRC client, authenticate with a password, choose a nickname, join channels, exchange messages, and use common channel management commands.

The project focuses on network programming, event-driven architecture, protocol parsing, and robust client management in C++.

## Features

* TCP server using IPv4 sockets
* Multiple client handling
* Non-blocking I/O
* IRC-style command parsing
* Password-based server authentication
* Nickname and user registration
* Channel creation and joining
* Private messages between users
* Channel messages
* Channel operators
* Basic IRC commands implementation
* Error handling and protocol replies
* Clean client disconnection handling

## Implemented Commands

The server supports common IRC commands such as:

```text
PASS
NICK
USER
JOIN
PRIVMSG
KICK
INVITE
TOPIC
MODE
PART
QUIT
PING
```

Some commands may be implemented according to the project requirements and may not cover the full official IRC specification.

## Technologies Used

* C++
* Unix sockets
* TCP/IP networking
* Non-blocking file descriptors
* poll/select-based event loop
* IRC protocol concepts
* Makefile

## Build

Clone the repository:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/Mohahamdali/ft_irc.git
cd ft_irc
```

Compile the project:

```bash
make
```

Clean object files:

```bash
make clean
```

Remove object files and executable:

```bash
make fclean
```

Rebuild the project:

```bash
make re
```

## Usage

Run the server with a port and password:

```bash
./ircserv <port> <password>
```

Example:

```bash
./ircserv 6667 mypassword
```

Then connect using an IRC client such as `irssi`:

```bash
irssi
/connect localhost 6667 mypassword
```

Or with `nc` for basic manual testing:

```bash
nc localhost 6667
```

Example manual registration:

```text
PASS mypassword
NICK john
USER john 0 * :John Doe
JOIN #general
PRIVMSG #general :Hello everyone
```

