## Core Concepts

### Server

The server is responsible for creating the listening socket, accepting new clients, monitoring file descriptors, receiving data, parsing commands, and sending replies.

### Client

Each connected user is represented as a client object. The client stores information such as socket file descriptor, nickname, username, authentication state, and joined channels.

### Channel

Channels allow multiple users to communicate together. A channel can contain regular users and operators. Operators can manage the channel through commands such as `KICK`, `INVITE`, `TOPIC`, and `MODE`.

### Command Handling

Incoming messages are parsed into commands and arguments. Each command is validated and executed according to the client state and IRC rules.

## Example Session

```text
PASS mypassword
NICK alice
USER alice 0 * :Alice
JOIN #chat
PRIVMSG #chat :Hello from ft_irc
```

Another client can join the same channel:

```text
PASS mypassword
NICK bob
USER bob 0 * :Bob
JOIN #chat
PRIVMSG #chat :Hello Alice
```

## Learning Objectives

This project helped me understand:

* How TCP servers work
* How to manage multiple clients at the same time
* How non-blocking I/O works
* How IRC protocol messages are structured
* How to design a command dispatcher
* How to manage users, channels, and permissions
* How to write more structured C++ code for a real networked application

## Limitations

This project is an educational IRC server and does not aim to fully implement every detail of the official IRC protocol. Some advanced IRC features may be missing or simplified.

